@NODE "CFGTHOR" "Configuring Thor"
@TOC "MAIN"

 @{b}Configuring Thor
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 You will probably want Thor to run SortMail every time you enter the system
 containing your email conference.  To do this select SortMail.br in the
 "Entering system" string gadged in ConfigThor -> System Configuration ->
 @{" Files/Paths window " ALINK "ConfigTHOR.guide/Files-Paths"}.

 If you want SortMail to run every time you enter your Email conference,
 enter SortMail.br in the "Entering conference" string gadget in the
 Conference Configuration ->  @{" Files/Paths window " ALINK "ConfigTHOR.guide/Files-Paths"} window.

 SortMail.br and CfgSortMail.thor can also be to assigned hotkeys by
 selecting "Add Script" or "Edit Definition" in the @{" ARexx Script " ALINK "THOR.guide/Menus"} menu.

 Also, if you want to run @{" Local2Email.thor " LINK "L2EMAIL"} on exiting, configure it as the
 "Leaving system" script.

 SortMail can be run on any number of systems if you have more than one
 mail box.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "CFGSORTMAIL" "Configuring SortMail"
@TOC "MAIN"

 @{b}Configuring SortMail
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 CfgSortMail.thor will let you configure SortMail using listview based GUI.
 Before you start the configuration, I recommend you at least take a browse
 through the below links.  It is also a good idea to take a look at the
 @{" Frequently Asked Questions " LINK "FAQ"} and @{" Hints and tips " LINK "HINT"} sections.


 Running CfgSortMail.thor
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 You can find CfgSortMail.thor in the rexx/ subdirectory of the directory
 where Thor is located.  It must be run from Thor and you can start it by
 selecting "Execute Script" in the @{" ARexx Script " ALINK "THOR.guide/Menus"} menu or configure it to a
 hotkey by selecting "Add Script" in the same menu.

 CfgSortMail assumes you want to configure the system you have entered or
 alternatively the system that is highlighted in the Startup Window.


 Using the listviews
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Here's how to navigate through the listviews:

 · You can use the mouse or the cursor keys to select the item you want to
   configure.  Doubleclicking, selecting the "Ok" button or pressing
   <RETURN> will activate the selected item.

   You will always recieve a short description of the option you are
   configuring when activating it.  For a more detailed description check
   out the links below.

 · In the main window and the trigger configuration windows there are "Save"
   or "Accept" options at the bottom of the listview.  When you're done,
   activate one of these.

   If you change your mind, the "Cancel" button (or alternatively pressing
   <ESC>) will abort the configuration and forget any changes made.


 Picking up data from the current message in Thor
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Most string requesters can pick up data from the message currently
 displayed in Thor's main window.  To make configuration easier, you should
 make sure to have a sample message available.

 The requesters which allow this have a Pickup button.  Just select it and
 CfgSortMail will get what you need.


 Online help
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 If you are running Workbench 3.1 or higher some listviews will have a
 "HELP" entry in the bottom of the listview.  Select this to get
 descriptions of the available configuration entries.


 The configuration windows
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

   @{" The main window                  " LINK "CFGSM_MAIN"}  Global options, saving

   @{" Trigger configuration            " LINK "CFGSM_TRIG"}  Trigger options, search & action lists

   @{" Search configuration             " LINK "CFGSM_SRCH"}  Search criterias

   @{" Action configuration             " LINK "CFGSM_ACTN"}  Actions to be performed on found message

@ENDNODE

@NODE "CFGSM_MAIN" "The main window"
@TOC "CFGSORTMAIL"

 @{b}The main window
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 The main window will let you configure the global attributes and maintain
 the triggers.

 These are the available entries:


 Email conference
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 This is the name of the Email conference.  In most cases this will be
 "Email".  When activated, a listview will pop up displaying all the
 conferences in the Email system configured above.


 Create statistics
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 You can make SortMail return statistics on its doings by activating this
 option.  The stats will be written as a message addressed to you in the
 Email conference.

 This option is also available from the command line as STATISTICS if you
 run SortMail from the Shell.


 Display warnings
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 On non fatal errors SortMail will usually pop up a requester describing
 the error and asking whether the user want to continue or not.  If this
 option is activated SortMail will skip these error messages.  This does
 not apply to fatal or potentially fatal errors, of course.

 Warnings will be shown in the report SortMail generates when it is
 finished, regardless of the state of this option.

 This option is also available from the command line as NOWARN if you run
 SortMail from the Shell.


 Use messages' login state
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 When run from Thor, SortMail has to processing modes:

 · All messages that were marked as unread when the user entered the
   current system will be processed.  This option is activated by setting
   this option to yes.

 · Process all messages currently marked as unread.  Activated by setting
   this option to no.

 Most users will prefer the first option in conjuction with SortMail run as
 a login script, since it guarantees that all incoming messages gets sorted.

 This option is also available from the command line as LOGINSTATE if you
 run SortMail from the Shell.  It must then be used together with the
 SHANGHAI switch.


 Add trigger
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Select this to add a @{" trigger " LINK "CFGSM_TRIG"}.  A fresh trigger configuration listview
 will pop up.


 Edit trigger
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Select this to edit a @{" trigger " LINK "CFGSM_TRIG"}.  A list of all the currently configured
 triggers will pop up.


 Rearrange triggers
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 If you want to change the order of the triggers select this entry.  You
 will then be presented with a list of all the triggers.  Selecting one of
 them will allow you to move it up, down or to the top or bottom of the
 list.

 When you are finished, pressing the Cancel button will return you to the
 main window.


 Delete trigger
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Select this to delete a trigger.  A window will open with a list of the
 currently selected triggers.


 Save and exit
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 When you are done configuring, activate this entry to save the
 configuration and leave CfgSortMail.

 If you for some reason don't want to save the configuration, select the
 "Cancel" button in the bottom of the listview.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "CFGSM_TRIG" "Trigger configuration"

 @{b}Trigger configuration
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 For each message type you want SortMail to process, you define a trigger.
 They consist of any number of search criterias and actions to perform on
 the messages that matches the search criterias.


 Name
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Choose a name that describes what the trigger is configured to do.  For
 example, a trigger that moves the ClassAct mailing list messages might be
 called "ClassAct mailing list".


 Delete message
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 The original message can be deleted if all the actions were performed
 successfully.  Useful when copying messages to another conference.

 Due to the nature of Thor's database the message will only be @{b}marked@{ub} as
 deleted when this option is activated.  The actual deletion of the message
 will not be done until a @{" purge " ALINK "Thor.guide/Pack-Purge Window"} is performed.


 Delete user
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 If user adding is turned on in ConfigThor -> System Configuration ->
 Import/Export, authors of messages in the Email conference are always
 added to the user database.

 If you activate this option, SortMail will delete these users provided they
 have written a message processed by the trigger you are configuring.  If
 the author already has an entry in the user database, it will not be
 deleted.


 Match all criterias
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 If set to "YES" all configured search criterias must be matched in order
 for SortMail to recognise a message.  Otherwise only one of the criterias
 must be matched.


 Add search entry
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Select this to add a new @{" search " LINK "CFGSM_SRCH"} entry.


 Add action entry
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Select this to add a new @{" action " LINK "CFGSM_ACTN"} entry.


 Search entries
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Below this line is a list of all the search entries configured in the
 current trigger.  Selecting one of them will pop up a requester asking you
 if you want to edit or delete it.


 Action entries
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Below this line is a list of all the action entries configured in the
 current trigger.  Selecting one of them will pop up a requester asking you
 if you want to edit or delete it.


 Accept and return
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 When you are done configuring, activate this entry to keep this trigger
 configuration and return to the @{" main window " LINK "CFGSM_MAIN"}.

 If you for some reason don't want to keep the trigger configuration,
 select the "Cancel" button in the bottom of the listview.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "CFGSM_SRCH" "Search configuration"

 @{b}Search configuration
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 When searching for messages to process SortMail will try to match
 configured strings in the messages' address, name, subject and header
 fields.  When a match is found SortMail will then perform any configured
 actions.

 Note that SortMail always searches for strings and not entire fields or
 words.  For example, if you configure SortMail to search for @aminet.org
 in the from address then all messages sent from that domain will be
 processed.  Specifying a whole address, like eirikns@sn.no, will make sure
 only messages from that specific address gets processed.  The same applies
 to all other searchable fields.

 Another thing to be aware of is that when a match is found and actions are
 performed, no other triggers will be executed on that specific message.
 SortMail will just proceed to the next message after having performed the
 actions defined in the trigger.

 In order to be as quick as possible SortMail will always perform any
 header searches last.

 
 Adding or editing a search entry
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 When adding a search entry you will get a list of the searchable fields.
 See below for a description.  This list will not be available when editing
 an entry.

 Next CfgSortMail will open a string requester where you should enter the
 string you want to search for.  The string searches are not case
 sensitive.


 The searchable fields
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 From address           Email address of the message's author as shown in
                        the "From:" field in Thor's main window

 From name              The author's name as shown in the "From:" field in
                        Thor's main window

 To address             The recipient's address as shown in the "To:" field
                        in Thor's main window

 To name                The recipient's name as shown in the "To:" field in
                        Thor's main window

 Subject                The message's subject as shown in the "Subject:"
                        field in Thor's main window

 Reply-To               The Reply-To: field in the header as shown in Thor's
                        message list. (hit the button in the upper right
                        corner of Thor's message display to show headers)


 Searching in the header
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Searching in the header will increase the time SortMail uses to process
 the messages by at least 50%, so you should avoid it and use the above
 fields if possible.  However, sometimes there is no other way.

 Header searches work like this: first SortMail finds a line which begins
 with a configured keyword.  When found it tries to match the configured
 criteria string with that header line.

 When configuring you will first be asked for the keyword.  Selecting the
 Pickup button will display the header of the message currently displayed
 in Thor's main window allowing you to select the line you want.

 Common lines to search in are "From", "Cc:", "Bcc:" and "Organization:".

 Next up is the criteria.  Simply enter a string that you want to search
 for on the line you picked.

 PS: To view a header in Thor, hit the small button in the top right corner
 of Thor's main window.

 PPS: When you view a header in Thor's main window, you might see a
 "Reply-To:" field.  This field is @{b}not@{ub} in the header as SortMail reads
 it, Thor just shows it there since there's no other place to show it. If
 you want to search in the Reply-To: field, use the configuration item
 mentioned above.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "CFGSM_ACTN" "Action configuration"

 @{b}Action configuration
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 A triggers' actions are performed when a message has matched the search
 criterias for that specific trigger.  Currently there are two types of
 triggers, internal and external.  Internal triggers are procedures within
 SortMail.br, external ones are seperate ARexx scripts.

 SortMail will first execute the internal actions in given order, then the
 external ones.  If any of the actions return with a warning, further
 execution of actions within that trigger will not be executed.  In some
 cases a requester will pop up with options to continue or abort.


 Adding or editing an action entry
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 When adding an action entry you will get a list of the available actions.
 See below for a description.  This list will not be available when editing
 an entry.


 The available actions
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

   @{" Copy messages to another conference " LINK "COPYMSG"}

   @{" Parse AmiNet RECENT message         " LINK "PARSEREC"}

   @{" Save message to disk                " LINK "SAVEMSG"}

   @{" Split digest                        " LINK "SPLITDIG"}

   @{" Run an external ARexx script        " LINK "RUNEXT"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "COPYMSG" "Copy messages to another conference"
@TOC "CFGSM_ACTN"

 @{b}Copy messages to another conference
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}
 This action will copy a message from the Email conference to another
 conference.  If the destination conference doesn't exist, SortMail will
 create it automatically the first time a message is copied.


 Configuration
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 First select the system and conference you want to copy the message to.  In
 the conference listview there is a "Create new conference" entry.  If you
 select it a string requester will ask for the name of the new conference.

 Next you will be asked to enter an address which replies will be directed
 to.  If you don't want to specify a reply-address, press the Cancel button.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "PARSEREC" "Parse AmiNet RECENT message"
@TOC "CFGSM_ACTN"

 @{b}Parse AmiNet RECENT message
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 It is possible to recieve daily or weekly new-files updates from AmiNet.
 (see how in the @{" FAQ " LINK "FAQ" 4}).  SortMail can parse these messages into the
 file database where the information will be stored for future access.
 After parsing the RECENT message will be deleted, but first it will be
 saved to the NewFiles.txt file in the BBS's directory from where it can be
 viewed in the "New files" window.

 If the RECENT message contains a "Message of the Day" or any statistics
 these will be added to SortMail's log message assuming you have configured
 SortMail otherwise.


 Excluding directories
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 You can prevent SortMail from adding files from certain directories by
 creating a file called SortMail.excl in the systems directory.  To find out
 where your system's directory is, enter this line in a Shell window:

   List `GetEnv THOR/BBSDATAPATH` DIRS LFORMAT "System: %-20c Path: %p%s"

 For each directory you want to exclude, add a line in SortMail.excl with
 the directory name as it appears in Thor's file database.  To exclude a
 directory and all it's children enter the name without any slashes

 Example:

   comms/ums
   demo
   mods
   mus/midi
   pix/wb

 You will still be able to see the excluded files in the "New Files" window,
 but they won't be added to the file database.


 Configuration
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 First you will be asked whether you want the new files to be parsed into
 the file database.  If not, the files will only be displayed in the New
 Files window.  This option is useful on slower machines, as adding files to
 the database can be slow.

 The next thing to configure is duplicate checking.  This will prevent
 SortMail from adding several entries of the same file in the database, but
 it slows down parsing considerably.

 Last you will be asked if you want to display "message of the day" and
 statistics in SortMail's log messages.  If you select no and also have
 SortMail configured to delete RECENT messages after processing them, these
 will vanish into a black hole.  I suggest you select yes unless you find
 them very annoying.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "SPLITDIG" "Split digest"
@TOC "CFGSM_ACTN"

 @{b}Split digest
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}
 This action will split MIME multipart digests and other common digest
 formats into seperate messages and optionally move them over to a seperate
 conference.

 If the destination conference doesn't exist, SortMail will create it
 automatically the first time a digest is splitted.

 
 How to identify a MIME digest
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 The easiest way to tell if one of the ones you are subscribing to uses
 MIME, is to look at how Thor displays the message.  If messages inside the
 digests are seperated with thick bars, then it is a MIME digest.


 How to identify other digest formats
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 In order for SortMail to recognize and split non-MIME digests there is few
 criterias to be met.  The digest must

   · contain a From: field in the beginning of each sub-message.  Date: and
     Subject: fields are optional.  All other fields will be ignored

   · seperate each sub-message with one line containing one repeated ASCII
     character, for example a line consisting of = signs.  This line must
     contain more than 30 characters

   · not include MIME message or binary parts


 Possible problems
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Since digest formats vary quite a lot it's quite possible you will run into
 a digest SortMail either won't split or splits in an incorect manner.  For
 that reason you should @{b}always@{ub} check whether SortMail splits it correctly
 or not.  Do so by configuring a Split digest action event, but don't
 activate Delete message in it's trigger configuration.

 If you do come across a digest that won't parse correctly then please mail
 me a copy of the digest together with any errors it produced and I will see
 if I can add support for it.


 Configuration
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 First select the system and conference you want to copy the message to.  In
 the conference listview there is a "Create new conference" entry.  If you
 select it a string requester will ask for the name of the new conference.

 Next you will be asked to enter an address which replies will be directed
 to.  If you don't want to specify a reply-address, press the Cancel button.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "SAVEMSG" "Save message to disk"
@TOC "CFGSM_ACTN"

 @{b}Save message to disk
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 This action saves messages from Thor's database to disk.  You can choose
 whether you want to write the message to a file or to a directory.  If you
 choose to write it to a directory, the subject will be used as filename.
 You can also shorten the subject, so that it will fit into AmigaDOS' 30
 character filename limitation.

 When using the subject as filename, SortMail will strip away unwanted
 characters (wilcard symbols, etc.) and any occurances of "Re: " in the
 filename before saving.

 Messages can be append to existing files and be made to include the header.
 The latter also applies to all message parts when dealing with MIME
 multipart messages.  It will also copy binary message parts to the download
 directory unless NOBIN has been specified.


 Configuration
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 First you will be asked whether you want to save to a file or to a
 directory.  Select one of them and a file requester will pop up asking for
 a file or directory name.

 If you chose to save to a directory you will then be asked whether you want
 to substitute part of the subject (which will be used as filename) with
 another string.  Selecting yes will bring up to requesters, the first one
 asking for the string to substitute and the second the string to substitute
 with.

 The final three requesters allow you to chose whether or not to append the
 messages to existing files, write headers and copy binary parts to the
 download directory configured in Thor.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "RUNEXT" "Run an external ARexx script"
@TOC "CFGSM_ACTN"

 @{b}Run an external ARexx script
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Through the use of external ARexx scripts you can add your own functions to
 SortMail.  Please see the section on @{" Creating external scripts " LINK "CREATESCRPT"} if you
 want to write your own.


 Configuration
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 First choose the ARexx script to execute in the file requester.  Afterwards
 a string requester will pop up asking for command line options.  Please see
 the documentation for that particular script for a list of available
 options.

 SortMail will also let you insert some tags into the option string.  A list
 of these tags and what they will translate to when the script is run is
 displayed in the requester.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "RUNTHOR" "Running SortMail from Thor"
@TOC "Main"

 @{b}Running SortMail from Thor
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 SortMail can be run from Thor in three ways:

   · by running it from the @{" ARexx Scripts menu " ALINK "THOR.guide/Menus"}.  You might want to assign
     it to a hotkey.

   · every time you enter your email conference.  To do this select your
     Email conference in the ConfigThor -> Conference Configuration window.
     Next enter SortMail.br in the "Entering Confs" string gadged in the
     @{" Files/Paths window " ALINK "ConfigTHOR.guide/Files-Paths"}.

   · every time you enter the system containing your email conference.  To
     do this select SortMail.br in the "Entering system" string gadged in
     ConfigThor -> System Configuration -> @{" Files/Paths window " ALINK "ConfigTHOR.guide/Files-Paths"}.

 The first time you run SortMail, you might want to make it process all
 messages in the email conference.  See @{" Running SortMail from the Shell " LINK "RUNSHELL"}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "RUNSHELL" "Running SortMail from the Shell"
@TOC "Main"

 @{b}Running SortMail from the Shell
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 The first time SortMail is run from the Shell it will have to go through
 each and every message in the email conference, since it doesn't know what
 messages was processed last time.  It will take some time, but it is a once
 only affair.  While you're at it, you might want to use the ALL/S switch to
 make sure all the messages, even those you have already read, will get
 processed.  A proper command line would be:

   rx `GetEnv THOR/THORPATH`rexx/SortMail.br "<system name>" NOCOUNTER ALL

 SortMail keeps track of the last message processed by writing its message
 number to the file SortMail.count in the system's directory.  This only
 applies when running SortMail from the Shell without the SHANGHAI or MSGNO
 arguments.


 Why should I run SortMail from the Shell?
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 If you are using an AmigaDOS or ARexx script for grabbing mail you might
 want to run SortMail after each grab.  This can be done by adding the
 following line to the script:

   rx `GetEnv THOR/THORPATH`rexx/SortMail.br "<system>" NOWARN QUIET

 When running SortMail from the Shell you can also

 · specify the exact message(s) you want to process (MSGNK/K/N)
 · process all messages, even the read ones, in your Email conference (ALL/S
   and NOCOUNTER/S)
 · "borrow" an available Thor port and make SortMail get the array of
   messages to process from it (SHANGHAI/S)


 Command template
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Usage       rx SortMail.br "<system name>" [ALL] [MSGNO <1stnumber> ...
             <nthnumber>] [SHANGHAI] [LOGINSTATE] [NOWARN] [QUIET]
             [NOCOUNTER]

 Template    SYSTEM/A,MSGNO/K/N/M,SHANGHAI/S,LOGINSTATE/S,NOWARN/S,
             NOCOUNTER/S,ALL/S,QUIET/S

 Arguments   SYSTEM/A is the name of the system containing the messages you
             want to process.

             When ALL/S is specified all messages, even those that are
             marked as read, will be processed.

             With MSGNO/K/N/M you can specify the messages to process by
             the numbers they have been assigned in the database.

             SHANGHAI/S will "shanghai" the Thor's ARexx port and use it to
             get a list of unread messages to process.  This is the quickest
             method.  If no Thor port is available SortMail will fall back
             to using the counter

             If you are running Thor 2.31 or older SortMail will only be
             able to get the message stem from the active system in Thor.
             With Thor 2.32 this is no longer relevant.

             Also, if both SHANGHAI/S and LOGINSTATE/S is specified
             SortMail get a list of the messages that were unread when the
             user entered the system.

             NOWARN/S will prevent SortMail from displaying low priority
             warning messages.  In most cases these are non-fatal.  They
             will still be recorded in the log message SortMail writes.

             If you don't want SortMail to display progress indication,
             use the QUIET/S switch.

             NOCOUNTER/S makes SortMail process every message in the Email
             conference.  It might be useful together with the ALL/S switch
             to clean up the conference.

             Note that SortMail will update the number of the last message
             processed, even though NOCOUNTER/S is specified.

 Example     rx SortMail.br "Mail & News" MSGNO 1025 1027 1030 NOWARN

@ENDNODE

@NODE "RUNCMD" "RunCommand.br"
@TOC "Main"

 @{b}RunCommand.br
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}
 RunCommand.br will execute a command.  One area of use might be to play a
 sample whenever a message is received from a certain person.

 If the command exits with an error, RunCommand will display the first line
 of output the command showed and present it as an error message.


 Command template
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Usage      rx RunCommand.br COMMAND <command> [OPTIONS <options>] [ASYNC]

 Template   COMMAND/A,OPTIONS/A,ASYNC/S

 Arguments  COMMAND/A is the name of the executable you want to run.

            OPTIONS/K is any command line arguments to pass to the command.

            If ASYNC/S is specified the command will be run in the
            background.  Otherwise RunCommand will wait until the command
            has finished before proceeding.

 Example    rx RunCommand.br COMMAND "Play16" OPTIONS
            "Work:Samples/Misc/NewsJingle.iff" ASYNC

@ENDNODE
@NODE "CREATESCRPT" "Creating external scripts"
@TOC "Main"

 @{b}Creating external scripts
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}
 For an example of how to write external scripts for SortMail, take a look
 at RunCommand.br.  This script contains most routines needed for proper
 interaction with SortMail.br and is a suitable basis for your own
 scripts.


 Command line arguments
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 SortMail can be configured to pass certain arguments to an external script.
 These are:

   %s  returns the system name
   %c  returns the email conference name
   %n  returns the number of the message
   %p  returns the name of Thor's ARexx port

 SortMail will add double quotes (") around %s, %c and %p so the user will
 not have to worry about this.

 The easiest way to parse command line arguments is to use bbsread's
 @{" READARGS " ALINK "BBSReadRexx.guide/READARGS"} command.  By using this instead of ARexx' own parse arg you
 don't have to worry about quotes and spaces in the arguments.


 Error handling
 @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}
 SortMail uses the rx command to execute external scripts.  The output of
 the script is redirected to a temporary file which will only be read if
 the script exits with an error code.  SortMail will then read one line from
 the temporary file and display this in its log.

 With other words, the only output an external script should produce should
 be error messages and it should be restricted to one line.

 The most important thing to remember is to @{i}always return proper error
 codes@{ui}.  If the trigger that executes your script is configured to
 delete the original message it will @{i}always@{ui} do so unless your
 script returns with a warning, failure or error.  So always use the
 exit(@{i}rc@{ui}) command when leaving the script.

 Here is how SortMail will react to different return codes:


      rc value  Type           Reaction
      @{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ  ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ  ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}
       1 -  5   Warning        SortMail will display the error, unless the
                               NOWARN command line and/or configuration
                               option has been specified, in which case
                               the warning will only show up in the log

       6 - 20   Error          SortMail will display the error and let the
                               user decide whether to continue processing
                               messages or not

      21 - 30   Fatal error    SortMail will display the error and exit


 @{i}Warnings@{ui} should be given on occasions where non-fatal errors occur, such as
 message doesn't contain what your script expects it to contain or you
 simply want the user to be aware of something.

 @{i}Errors@{ui} should be given when an error occurs, but which is only relevant to
 the execution of your particular script.  This could be incorrect command
 line options, retrieval of non-existant or deleted messages and the like.

 @{i}Fatal errors@{ui} must be given if there is a possibility that SortMail or other
 scripts can be affected by the error.  This includes errors from most
 BBSRead ARexx commands that interface the message, user or file databases
 as they could imply that the database is corrupt.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "FAQ" "Frequently Asked Questions"
@TOC "Main"

 @{b}Frequently Asked Questions
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 Question:
 How do I subscribe to the AmiNet RECENT mailing list?

 Answer:
 Send a mail to listproc@mail.wustl.edu with "subs aminet-daily <your name>"
 in the message body to subscribe to the daily list or "subs aminet-weekly
 <your name>" to subscribe to the weekly list.


 Question:
 SortMail is slow.  How can I make it run faster?

 Answer:
 · Avoid searching in the header, but stick to addresses, names and subjects
   If no header searches are configured in any of the triggers you can
   expect SortMail to be at least 30% faster

 · The fewer messages in the Email conference, the faster SortMail runs.
   Use Pack/Purge every once in a while with a low "Messages/Days to keep"
   value

 · Increase the size of buffers in ConfigThor -> Database Options.
   Usually 20000 bytes is a good setting, but of course this will eat lots
   of precious memory.  Increasing the number of buffers will usually not
   give any significant speed increase.  A bit of experimentation is
   definately needed

 · Don't activate deleting of users in the trigger configurations

 · Don't check for duplicates when parsing AmiNet RECENT updates into the
   file database

 · Run Maintainance in the file and user database every once in a while


 Question:
 I want SortMail to move my sent mail to another conference.  How can I do
 that?

 Answer:
 Create a new trigger called "Sent mail" or similar.  Configure it to search
 for your own Email address in the from address field and to copy the
 messages to another conference.

 If you subscribe to mailing lists you might want messages you have written
 to one of these to end up in the mailing list's conference.  To do that,
 make sure the "Sent mail" trigger is last on the list of triggers using
 "Rearrange triggers" in the @{" main window " LINK "CFGSM_MAIN"}.

 If you want all your sent mail to be moved to the "Sent mail" conference
 make sure the trigger is always the first on the trigger list.


 Question:
 SortMail doesn't split digests correctly.  What can I do.

 Answer:
 Since digest formats vary quite a lot it's difficult to add support for all
 of them.  Mail me a copy of the digest and any error messages it produces
 and I'll se if I can add support for it.  Also see @{" Split digest " LINK "SPLITDIG"}.


 Question:
 When I use "Delete duplicates" in Thor, duplicate messages in conferences
 created by digest parsing aren't deleted.  Why not?

 Answer:
 Thor deletes messages with the same message id.  Splitted digest messages
 don't get their own id since there is no unique message id for each of the
 submessages in most digests.  The result is that Thor can't detect
 duplicates in these conferences.


 Question:
 When I grab my new mail some messages seem to disappear when parsed into
 Thor.  Does Thor or SortMail eat Email or what!?

 Answer:
 Nope, they don't.  When you grab your mail you get a copy of every message
 you've mailed since the last time you grabbed mail.  Also, if you wrote a
 message to a mailing list or digest you will in addition get another copy
 from the mailing list or digest server.  All these messages are per default
 automatically marked as read when they are written to Thor's database.  So
 they're in your message database, but you won't see them unless you use
 the All read-mode.

 If you don't want your messages to be marked as read you can change the
 setting for this in ConfigThor's Conference or System configuration under
 Import/Export -> Database Options.  This is a smart thing to do anyway,
 otherwise the Email you send out won't be processed by SortMail.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "HINT" "Hints and tips"
@TOC "Main"

 @{b}Hints and tips
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 · SortMail skips messages marked as Super Unread.  So if you want a
   message to permanently stay in your Email conference without being
   processed, mark it as Super Unread.


 · Copying messages to separate conferences is not only useful for mailing
   lists and the like.  You can also do it with messages from certain
   persons by specifying their address in the search configuration.  Also
   see the text about moving your own messages into a seperate conference in
   the @{" Frequently Asked Questions " LINK "FAQ"} section.


 · It is possible to create a "pseudo-mailing list" using Thor, SortMail and
   Local2Email.  Here is how to do it:

   1. Create a new user in the @{" User Database Window " ALINK "THOR.guide/User_database"} with all the
      addresses of the mailing lists members in the Address field seperated
      with commas.  You must also choose a user name.

      Both name and addresses must be identical in each member's User
      database.  It must also be updated by all members every time a user
      is added or removed from the mailing list.  This can be automated
      by writing an external ARexx script.  If you do, please mail it to me
      and I'll be happy to include it in the SortMail distribution.

   2. Configure a trigger in @{" CfgSortMail " LINK "CFGSORTMAIL"} which does the following:
      - searches for the name you chose in the User database
      - copies the messages to another conference
      - sets the reply address to the @{i}name@{ui} you chose in the User database

   3. Configure Local2Email.br as the "Leaving System" script in CfgThor ->
      System -> @{" Files/Paths window " ALINK "ConfigTHOR.guide/Files-Paths"}.

   ...and you're ready to go.

   When writing messages to the list, just make sure you're in the mailing
   list conference.  Local2Email.br will automatically fill in the correct
   addresses and change the conference to your Email conference when it is
   run.

   The above procedre means that all members of the list must use Thor.

@ENDNODE

